{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20878"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96605"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13753"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79239"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11592"},{"type":"tags","id":"11593"},{"type":"tags","id":"12701"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33118"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96605"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of microRNAs in gene regulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Directly encode small peptides","Activate transcription of protein-coding genes","Catalyse RNA splicing reactions","Bind to complementary mRNA sequences to regulate expression","Serve as templates for DNA replication"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding to complementary mRNA sequences to regulate expression\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of microRNAs (miRNAs). These small noncoding RNAs (approximately 22 nucleotides in length) typically bind to the 3\u0027 untranslated region of target messenger RNAs. This binding leads to either translational repression or mRNA degradation, resulting in gene silencing at the post-transcriptional level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly encode small peptides\u003C/strong\u003E - By definition, noncoding RNAs including miRNAs do not encode proteins or peptides.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivate transcription of protein-coding genes\u003C/strong\u003E - miRNAs typically repress rather than activate gene expression, and they act post-transcriptionally rather than at the transcriptional level.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatalyse RNA splicing reactions\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the function of small nuclear ribonucleoproteins (snRNPs) in the spliceosome, not miRNAs.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EServe as templates for DNA replication\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA serves as its own template during replication; miRNAs are not involved in this process.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong noncoding RNAs (lncRNAs), the other major class of noncoding RNAs, are longer than 200 nucleotides and can regulate gene expression through various mechanisms including chromatin remodelling, transcriptional regulation, and post-transcriptional processing. Alterations in both miRNAs and lncRNAs have been implicated in various diseases, particularly cancer, where they can function as oncogenes or tumour suppressors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Noncoding RNAs include microRNAs (miRNAs) and long noncoding RNAs (lncRNAs) that serve important regulatory functions without encoding proteins.","MicroRNAs regulate gene expression by binding to complementary sequences in messenger RNA, typically resulting in gene silencing.","Long noncoding RNAs can regulate gene expression through various mechanisms including chromatin remodelling and transcriptional regulation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 143"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79239"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79239"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T11:55:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T11:56:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13753"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96605"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11592"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mutations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:52:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:52:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"gr